These results apply to detection results at a single detector and thus relate to first order coherence (see degree of coherence). However, for measurements correlating detections at multiple detectors, higher-order coherence is involved (e.g., intensity correlations, second order coherence, at two detectors). Glauber&#x27;s definition of quantum coherence involves nth-order correlation functions (n-th order coherence) for all . The perfect coherent state has all n-orders of correlation equal to 1 (coherent). It is perfectly coherent to all orders.

